        <p><strong>&#8594; To your local police force:</strong> How many crimes were reported in [Park Name] during the past 12 months? Please provide a breakdown by month and type of incident.</p>
        <p><strong>&#8594; To your local council:</strong> Please provide any internal reports or assessments about safety or lighting in [Park Name] in the last three years.</p>
      </div>

    </section>

    <section class="section-medium">
      <h3 id="find-out-who-might-have-the-information"><span class="label-tag">2</span>Find out who might have the information</h3>
      <p>Once you know what you want to ask, the next step is to work out who is likely to hold that information.</p>
      <p>This is important because your FOI request needs to be made to the organisation that holds the information. If you send it to the wrong place, you could get a “not held” response. You would then need to write to another organisation and that could take more time.</p>
      <p>If the information that you are interested in is local information, it might be held by your local council, police force or NHS trust.</p>
      <p>If you have a question about a national policy, it might be held by a government department such as the Home Office or DWP.</p>
      <p>Sometimes it might not be obvious who would hold the information you want.</p>
      <p>If you are not sure, you can try checking an authority’s website, or contacting the authority in advance.</p>
      <p>You can also search an authority’s name or a keyword on WhatDoTheyKnow, and find previous requests that others have made. This can give you a good idea about the types of information that an authority holds.</p>
      <p>Sometimes more than one organisation could have the relevant information.</p>
      <p>For example, if you wanted to find out information about a local community policing initiative, both the police and your local council might hold separate pieces of useful information (the police for crime statistics, the council for community safety meeting minutes). In that case, you might want to make a separate request to each authority.</p>
      <p>If you’re really unsure, don’t worry. If the authority that you ask doesn’t have the information, they will usually tell you who does.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section-medium">
      <h3 id="write-your-request"><span class="label-tag">3</span>Write your request</h3>
      <p>There is no strict format that you need to use, but it helps to be clear and specific.</p>
      <p>To be valid, a request needs to contain your real name, an address that you would like the information to be sent to, and a description of the information you are interested in. The address can be an email address or a postal address.</p>
      <p>You should clearly describe the information that you want, including information like dates, places or departments where applicable.</p>
      <p>You don’t need to justify why you are asking for the information. Try to focus on describing the information itself.</p>
      <p>Although the wider context of your request might be important to you, you should avoid including extra background information, unless it would help the FOI officer to locate the information that you are asking for.</p>
      <p>Requests to authorities in Wales can be made either in English or Welsh.</p>
      <p>If you would like to receive the information in a set format, for example in electronic format, you should say so at the time that you make your request. The authority has to comply with your request if it is reasonable for them to do so. If you need a special format due to accessibility (such as large print or an audio recording), you can request that too.</p>

