            </svg>
            Try to avoid broad requests
        </div>
        <p>Such as “all documents relating to [topic]”. These are more likely to be refused, as the law allows authorities to refuse to respond to requests if it would take too long for them to do so. If possible, try to narrow your request to a set time period or a specific project/event.</p>
      </div>
      <br>
      <div class="highlight-text">
        <p>Here is a quick checklist of the things that your request needs to contain:</p>
        <ul>
        <li>Your name.</li>
        <li>An email address or postal address for the authority to send the response to.</li>
        <li>A clear description of the information that you want.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-medium">
      <h3 id="send-the-request"><span class="label-tag">4</span>Send the request</h3>
      <p>Once you’ve written your request, and checked that it contains the necessary information, the next step is to send it to the authority.</p>

      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="card card-spawn-2">
          <h4 class="card-header">WhatDoTheyKnow</h4>
          <p>WhatDoTheyKnow is a website that enables you to make requests for free.</p>
          <p>There are over 45,000 public authorities listed on WhatDoTheyKnow and you can make requests to any of them.</p>
          <p>Your request, and any response that the authority provides, are published on the site. This automatic record is available in a public archive to help others.</p>
          <p>Please note that WhatDoTheyKnow will publish your request on the internet along with your username. If you are worried about your privacy or don’t want your request to be public, you are better off contacting the authority directly.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h4 class="card-header">Email</h4>
          <p>Almost every public authority has a dedicated email address for FOI requests.</p>
          <p>You can usually find it on their website on the “Freedom of Information” or “Contact us” pages.</p>
          <p>If not, any official email address will do. The law doesn’t require requests to be sent to a specific address. If you are using the general contact address, it’s a good idea to ask for your message to be forwarded to the FOI team.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h4 class="card-header">Online form</h4>
          <p>Some authorities have a dedicated webform on their website for making requests.</p>
          <p>These are often easy to use, but one downside is that you usually won’t have a copy of your request if you need it later on.</p>
          <p>You might want to take a screenshot or save the text of your request in a separate document so that you have a record of it. Make sure you note down the date your request was sent.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h4 class="card-header">Letter</h4>
          <p>FOI requests can be made by post.</p>
          <p>If you post your request at your local Post Office, you can ask for a free ‘proof of posting’ to show that you sent it.</p>
          <p>You should also keep a copy of the request that you sent for your records, as this will be helpful if you need to appeal.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h4 class="card-header">In person</h4>
          <p>You can hand deliver a request to the offices of the public authority.</p>
          <p>Some authorities have a postbox that you can leave letters in. You might be able to ask the receptionist to give you a receipt, as proof of the date they received it.</p>
          <p>As with a request made by post, you should keep a copy of the request that you sent, as this will be helpful if you need to appeal.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-medium">
      <h3 id="receive-a-response"><span class="label-tag">5</span>Receive a response</h3>
      <p>You should receive a response from the authority within 20 working days (around four weeks).</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section-medium">
      <h3 id="use-the-information"><span class="label-tag">6</span>Use the information</h3>
      <p>You might just have wanted the information for your own purposes.</p>
      <p>Or you can share the information you receive with others. It might be useful for a campaign, or to share on a blog or community group, in a letter to the newspaper or in a research paper.</p>
      <p>Some authorities will claim copyright over the material contained in the FOI request, but in practice authorities generally allow requesters to share FOI responses with others who may be interested.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 id="reasonable-adjustments">Reasonable adjustments</h2>
      <p>The FOI process is supposed to be accessible to everyone. Public authorities have a legal duty to remove barriers to people accessing their services.</p>
      <p>If you cannot easily make a request in writing due to a disability, you can ask the authority to accept your request in an alternative way. ICO guidance explicitly states that you can make a verbal request if you need a reasonable adjustment and the authority should help you to do so.</p>
      <p>You can also ask to receive the information in an accessible format. This might include receiving the information in braille, as a large print version or as an audio recording.</p>
      <p>When asking for an adjustment, it’s helpful to clearly explain what you need and why. If an authority fails to accommodate you, you can get advice from the Equality Advisory Support Service (EASS) or Citizens Advice.</p>
    </section>

